    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks! Now it makes sense!</p>\n<p>In the context of mathematics, my mental model (note: I'm not sure if my mental model has been correct!) has been that the expression a ‚àà ùîΩ represents a concept at the same level of specificity as a ‚àà ‚ÑÇ, meaning that I viewed both ùîΩ and ‚ÑÇ as sets with similar degrees of abstraction or concreteness.</p>\n<p>However, from a type-theoretic perspective, I recognize a distinction: ùîΩ can be seen as an abstract type, whereas ‚ÑÇ is a concrete instantiation of that type, effectively implementing the field interface that ùîΩ represents.</p>",
        "id": 424721338,
        "sender_full_name": "Isak Colboubrani",
        "timestamp": 1709577649
    }
